# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aeneid
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] The *Abora I* originated as a school project in Germany using locally grown Giant (Miscanthus).
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] All subsequent vessels were commissioned to boat builders from the Aymara nation living at Lake Titicaca in Bolivia; the same boat builders worked already for Thor Heyerdahl.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] As building material they used the very sturdy and durable Totora reed which is far better suited for this purpose.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] The Abora (or Abora I, in retrospective) was designed, built and used between 1996 and 1999.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] It sailed from Alghero (Sardinia, Italy) to Piombino (Tuscany, Italy).
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] The Abora II sailed in 2002 across the Mediterranean: from Alexandria (Egypt) to Beirut (Lebanon), Cyprus and back to Alexandria.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] It thus became the first modern-time reed boat which managed to complete an extended round trip and then to return to the port of departure.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] The departure at Alexandria coincided with the inauguration of the Bibliotheca Alexandrina, the new Alexandrian library; the Abora crew brought some gifts (books) from Thor Heyerdahl's Kon-Tiki Museum in Oslo, Norway in honor of the inauguration.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] Thor Heyerdahl had also personally supported the preparation of the Abora I and II expeditions; by coincidence the launch of the Abora II took place on 18 April 2002, which turned out to be the day when Thor Heyerdahl died.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] With Abora III, Dominique Görlitz attempted the first ever crossing of the Atlantic from West to East with a reed boat.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] Görlitz considered it possible that such events actually took place in antiquity.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] As a motivation, he particularly quoted the finding of traces of cocaine and nicotine in Egyptian mummies, including chopped tobacco leaves and the remains of a Mexican tobacco beetle in the mummy of Ramses II (1298–1213 BC).
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] Mainstream scholars have shown that there are possible Old World sources of cocaine and nicotine.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] The finding of tobacco leaves became a popular topic in fringe literature and the media and it was seen as proof of contact between Ancient Egypt and the New World.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] Compared to an East-West crossing, which Thor Heyerdahl successfully demonstrated in 1970 with the barely maneuverable reed boat Ra II, a west-east crossing of the Atlantic is much more difficult.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] This must be done further north along the Gulf Stream.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] However, the Gulf Stream does not flow evenly, but forms huge eddies.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] Furthermore, the winds there blow inconsistently from all directions.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] This means that this crossing cannot take place as a practically pure drift, as in the case of the Ra II in the opposite direction, rather the reed boat must be able to cover longer distances by wind even under adverse conditions.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] The hull of the boat was again manufactured in Bolivia (in 2006).
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] The boat was finalized one year later in New York.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] The *Abora III* expedition started in New York on July 11, 2007.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] An initially supportive Azores high dissolved completely in early August, and the crew faced one storm after another.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] Two of these storm lows reached hurricane strengths with wind speeds of up to 51 knots.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] These bad weather fronts affected the Abora III, but did not yet lead to serious damage.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] However, three side swords broke during the first storm, but this happened close enough to the American mainland that replacement swords could be delivered and replaced.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] In mid-August, after 500 km of a total of around 6000 km, a calm delayed the trip.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] A three-day hurricane then damaged the rear of the Abora III on August 27, 2007 in such a way that it had to be separated from the hull. during the subsequent 4 days, the crew reinstalled the intact rudder and moved the mast further towards the bow.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] The modified Abora III could temporarily set full sail and even sail up to 90° to the wind.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] On September 4, the next storm with wind force 10 severely affected both the Abora III and an escort vessel approaching from the Azores.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] Therefore, the crew abandoned the experiment on September 5, 2007, about 900 kilometres from the Azores, the 11-member crew and switched to the escort vessel.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] The reed boat was left to the sea after cutting the strings that held the hull together.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] A message in a bottle thrown into the water before the boat was evacuated was found in the Bahamas in October 2010.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] This illustrates that a West-East crossing of the Atlantic requires an intact sailing ability of the boat (in contrast to the opposite direction: Thor Heyerdahl's Ra II was also badly damaged in 1970, but was still able to drift to America with the help of the Canary Current).
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] The aim of the Abora IV expedition was to retrace possible trade contacts between the Black Sea and the Mediterranean.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] Herodotus mentioned in his *Histories* trading contacts between the Egyptians and the Caucasus on the eastern Black Sea coast; according to him, especially metals were imported into Egypt via this route.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] According to the expedition leader Dominique Görlitz's assumption, tin and amber were also exported from Central Europe to Egypt via the Balkans and finally the Black Sea to the Mediterranean.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] Varna in Bulgaria was chosen as the starting point of the expedition both because of the place's historic significance (Varna Necropolis) and for practical reasons; the expedition received strong support from the Varna Archaeological Museum.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] The final construction took place from May to August 2019 in Beloslav near Varna.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] Due to the late delivery of the prefabricated reed bundles from Bolivia and due to extremely bad weather conditions in Bulgaria, the launch of the Abora was greatly delayed and the start of the expedition could only take place on August 16.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] The Abora IV sailed through the Black Sea to Istanbul in Turkey, then through the Bosporus (on tow, for safety reasons), through the Marmara Sea and into the Dardanelles (again on tow) to Çanakkale (a modern harbor near ancient Troy), then onward into the Aegean Sea.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] Here, the first station was the Greek island of Limnos, where the vessel managed to enter and to leave the prehistoric port of Poliochni without being supported by a tug boat.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] From there, it sailed on to Santorini, hereby managing to pass several straits between several Greek islands.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] During the expedition, Dominique Görlitz received the offer from the Turkish Ministry of Culture in Ankara to exhibit the reed boat in the Patara Archeology Park (near Antalya) as a permanent exhibit.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] Thereupon it was decided to sail from Santorini straight to Kaş (a modern harbour near Patara) at the Lycian coast.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] Here, the Abora IV arrived on 19 September; the entire distance from Varna to Kaş was covered in 34 days.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] As planned, the vessel is now on permanent display on the agora of the ancient city of Patara.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] Like most experimental-archaeological projects, also the ABORA projects could only examine the technical feasibility of a proposed method.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] Whether these methods were indeed exploited in the past, can only be clarified by archaeological finds.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] The Abora expeditions specifically acclaimed to have reproduced an ancient navigation technology based on the use of leeboards.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] The expedition leader Dominique Görlitz presented various examples of such depictions (with and without leeboards) in his books and on the official project website.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] Ethnological evidence for the use of large navigable rafts exists only from South America, where such rafts were in use also after the Spanish conquest.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] These rafts used so-called centerboards or guaras; they could be navigated even without a rudder.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] Also Thor Heyerdahl conducted already some experiments using those guaras.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] Therefore, Heyerdahl followed the ABORA expeditions with great interest until his death in 2002.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] Positive appraisals of the ABORA projects came also from various other scientists, for instance Havva Iskan (Akdeniz University, Turkey, lead archaeologist at Patara, where the ABORA IV is now on permanent display).
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] In 2007, during the ABORA III expedition, a critical article appeared in the German popular-scientific journal *Spektrum der Wissenschaft*.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] It quotes a German Egyptologist who doubts Görlitz' interpretation of details of boat depictions as leeboards, as well as his assumptions with regard to the age of those depictions, but does not offer an alternative explanation.
[src:aeneid/abora-expeditions] Specifically with regard to the Abora III expedition (attempt of a West-East Atlantic crossing), doubts are also expressed about alleged evidences for tobacco or cocaine use in ancient Egypt.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] In ancient Roman religion, **Abundantia** (Latin pronunciation: [abʊnˈdantɪ.a]), also called **Copia**, was a divine personification of abundance and prosperity; *abundantia* means "abundance" in Latin.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] She helped protect savings and investments, and assisted with major purchases.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] She was among the embodiments of virtues in religious propaganda that cast the emperor as the ensurer of "Golden Age" conditions.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] Abundantia thus figures in art, cult, and literature, but has little mythology as such.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] She may have survived in some form in Roman Gaul and medieval France.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] Abundantia is depicted carrying a cornucopia filled with grain and coins, and was said to occasionally leave gifts from the horn at houses.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] The Augustan poet Ovid gives Abundantia a role in the myth of Acheloüs the river god, one of whose horns was ripped from his forehead by Hercules.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] The horn was taken by the naiads and transformed into the cornucopia that was granted to Abundantia.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] Other aetiological myths provide different explanations of the cornucopia's origin.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] On Neronian coinage, she was associated with Ceres and equated with Annona, who embodied the grain supply.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] Like Annona, Abundantia was a "virtue in action" in such locations as the harbor, where grain entered the city.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] Coinage in Rome depicts her either holding the cornucopia or pouring out the riches contained within the cornucopia.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] Occasionally she is depicted as holding wheat or standing on a ship.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] It is unknown what her appearance on ships represents.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] Abundantia appears on the medals of many emperors, such as Trajan, Antoninus Pius, Caracalla, Elagabalus, Severus Alexander, Gordian, Decius, Gallienus, Tetricus, Probus, Numerian, Carinus, Carus, Diocletian, and Galerius.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] She appears alongside one of several inscriptions: Abundantia, Abundantia Perpetua, Augustorum Nostrorum, Augustorum Augg NN, and Augustia Aug.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] Mithraic iconography on a vase from Lezoux, in the Roman province of Gallia Aquitania, depicts this deity seated and holding a cornucopia as a symbol of "the abundance that stems from Mithras' act".
[src:aeneid/abundantia] It has been suggested that the Gallic goddess Rosmerta had a functional equivalence to Abundantia, but the two are never directly identified in inscriptions.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] 1249), a bishop of Paris, mentions a Domina Abundia ("Mistress Abundia"), who also appears in the *Roman de la Rose* as "Dame Habonde." The bishop derives her name from *abundantia*.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] At night the *dominae* enter houses where offerings have been set out for them.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] They eat and drink from the vessels, but the contents are undiminished.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] If they are pleased, they bring prosperity and fertility.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] William regarded these practices as a form of idolatry.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] Folklorists of the 19th century saw these figures as Celtic fairies.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] Nicholas of Cusa reports that on his travels through the French Alps in 1457, he met two old women who told him they were in the service of Domina Abundia.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] They identified themselves as apostate Christians, and had been imprisoned for witchcraft.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] Nicholas felt that they had been deluded by the devil, but should be allowed to receive penance rather than burning at the stake.
[src:aeneid/abundantia] In later Western art, Abundantia is often portrayed holding her cornucopia and sheaves of corn or wheat.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] The **Abydos boats** are the remnants of a group of ancient royal Egyptian ceremonial boats found at an archaeological site in Abydos, Egypt.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] Discovered in 1991, excavation of the Abydos boats began in 2000 at which time fourteen boats were identified.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] They are located alongside the massive mudbrick structure known as Shunet El Zebib, attributed to the 2nd Dynasty Pharaoh Khasekhemwy.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] Shunet El Zebib is one of several such "enclosure wall" constructions at this site dating back to the Early Dynastic Period, and is located nearly one mile from the royal cemetery of Umm El Qa'ab.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] The University of Pennsylvania Museum and Yale University Expedition carried out the excavation of the Abydos boats.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] Lines of mudbrick uncovered by blowing sand were first noticed in 1988 at a site a mile away from the royal tombs in Abydos.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] These brick remains were first thought to be just walls.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] However, it was later determined that they were the boundaries for more than a dozen ship burials from an early dynasty.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] Each ship grave had its own brick boundary walls.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] The outline of each grave was in the shape of a boat, and the surface of each was covered with mud plaster and whitewash.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] Small boulders at the prow or stern of each grave represented anchors.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] Because of the fragility of the boat remains, almost no excavation was done initially as the situation had to be carefully studied for future conservation.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] 10, which was slowly appearing due to apparent soil erosion, was the only boat that was initially investigated.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] For five days, archaeologists carefully examined the midsection of the ship.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] They uncovered wooden planks, disintegrated rope, and reed bundles.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] Wood-eating ants had reduced much of the ship's hull to frass (ant excrement), but the frass had retained the shape of the original hull.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] The midsection of this boat revealed the construction methods used and confirmed the oldest ‘planked’ constructed boat yet discovered.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] The boat's construction revealed it had been constructed from the outside in, as there was no internal frame.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] Averaging 75 ft long and 7–10 ft wide at their greatest width, these boats were only about two feet deep, with narrow prows and sterns.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] Several boats were white-plastered, as were the Abydos tombs, and no.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] Seams between planks were filled with reed bundles, reeds also covered the floor of each Abydos boat.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] Without internal framing, some of these boats became twisted, as was unavoidable without an internal skeleton for support when out of the water.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] The wood of the Abydos boats was local *Tamarix* – tamarisk, salt cedar – not cedar from Lebanon which was used for Khufu’s Solar Barque and favored for shipbuilding in Egypt in later dynasties.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] Lebanon cedar was used for the poles and beams of the Umm el-Qa'ab tombs and had already been imported earlier; pigment residues hinted at bright colors.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] 29A cultural center.” This technology for ship construction persisted in Egypt for more than one thousand years and the standardization of this earliest phase of plank boat construction in Egypt is striking.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats were found in boat graves with their prows pointed towards the Nile.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] Experts consider them to have been the royal boats intended for the pharaoh in the afterlife.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] Umm el-Qa'ab is a royal necropolis that is about one mile from the Abydos boat graves where early pharaohs were entombed.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats are the predecessors of the great solar boats of later dynasties upon which the pharaoh joined the sun god Ra and together journeyed down the sacred Nile during the day.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] They would have had many of the important attributes and metaphors that were attached to the solar barques of later dynasties, and indeed perhaps should be called solar boats of an earlier design.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] The Khufu ship, built for the Pharaoh Khufu – Cheops – ca.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] 2500 BC., is usually identified as the earliest solar barque.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] It was buried in a pit at the foot of the Great Pyramid at Giza.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] The Abydos boat graves were adjacent to a massive funerary enclosure for the late Dynasty II (ca.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] 2675 B.C.) Pharaoh Khasekhemwy at Abydos which is eight miles from the Nile.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] Umm el-Qa'ab is a royal necropolis at Abydos where early pharaohs were entombed.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] However, these boat graves were established earlier than late in Dynasty II, perhaps for the afterlife journeys of Hor-Aha, the first king (ca.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] 2920–2770) of the First Dynasty of Egypt, or Pharaoh Djer also of Dynasty I.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] Two more recently located mortuary discoveries have been identified as those of King Aha, who may have been the son of the famous King Narmer, to whom the first unification of Upper and Lower Egypt is often attributed.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats are not the only find of First Dynasty ships.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] Nineteen boat burials were found at Helwan, but only four of these finds were published.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] Six boat graves were found at Saqqara by Walter Bryan Emery and four of these finds were published.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] Finally two full-sized model boats made out of clay are known from Abu Roash Hill.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] Helwan (a suburb of Cairo on eastern side of Nile) contain a huge cemetery field 20 km south of Cairo adjoining Saqqara in which at least 10,000 tombs have been cataloged.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] The size of Helwan indicates a very large population for Early Dynastic Memphis.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] Almost all the tombs date from Dynasty 0 through the Third Dynasty.
[src:aeneid/abydos-boats] There are 19 elite tombs where 1st Dynasty funeral boat burials have been discovered that resemble those at Abydos, but little published information is available.
[src:aeneid/acerbas] In this account Acerbas is the same person as Sychaeus, and Elissa the same as Dido in Virgil.
[src:aeneid/acerbas] The names in Justin are undoubtedly more correct than in Virgil; for Servius remarks, that Virgil here, as in other cases, changed a foreign name into one more convenient to him, and that the real name of Sychaeus was Sycharbas, which seems to be identical with Acerbas.
[src:aeneid/acestes] In Roman mythology, **Acestes** or **Egestes** (Ancient Greek: Ἀκέστης) was the son of the Sicilian river-god Crinisus by a Dardanian or Trojan woman named Egesta or Segesta.
[src:aeneid/acestes] When Egesta arrived in Sicily, the river-god Crinisus in the form of a bear or a dog sired with her a son named Acestes, who was afterwards regarded as the hero who had founded the town of Segesta.
[src:aeneid/acestes] The funeral games of Aeneas's father Anchises were held there.
[src:aeneid/acestes] Those of Aeneas's folk who wished to voyage no further were allowed to remain behind with Acestes and together with Acestes's people they founded the city of Acesta, that is Segesta.
[src:aeneid/acestes] The *Aeneid* cites him as giving wine as a farewell gift to Aeneas as he is leaving Sicily.
[src:aeneid/acestes] The tradition of Acestes in Dionysius of Halicarnassus, who calls him Aegestus (Αἴγεστος), is different, for according to him, the grandfather of Aegestus quarreled with Laomedon, who slew him and gave his daughters to some merchants to convey them to a distant land.
[src:aeneid/acestes] A noble Trojan however embarked with them, and married one of them in Sicily, where she subsequently gave birth to a son, Aegestus.
[src:aeneid/acestes] During the war against Troy Aegestus obtained permission from Priam to return and take part in the contest, and afterwards returned to Sicily, where Aeneas on his arrival was hospitably received by him and Elymus, and built for them the towns of Aegesta and Elyme.
[src:aeneid/acestes] The account of Dionysius seems to be nothing but a rationalistic interpretation of the genuine legend.
[src:aeneid/acestes] In the *Aeneid*, Acestes participates in a trial of skill in which he shoots his arrow which then bursts into flame as a sign from Jupiter of Acestes's deserved honor.
[src:aeneid/achaean-leaders] In Greek mythology, the **Achaean Leaders** were those who led the expedition to Troy to retrieve the abducted Helen, wife of Menelaus, king of Sparta.
[src:aeneid/achaean-leaders] Most of the leaders were bound by the Oath of Tyndareus who made the Suitors of Helen swear that they would defend and protect the chosen husband of Helen against any wrong done against him in regard to his marriage.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] The **Achaeans** or **Akhaians** (/əˈkiːənz/; Ancient Greek: Ἀχαιοί, romanized: *Akhaioí*, "the Achaeans" or "of Achaea") is one of the names in Homer which is used to refer to the Greeks collectively.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] The term "Achaean" is believed to be related to the Hittite term **Ahhiyawa** and the Egyptian term **Ekwesh** which appear in texts from the Late Bronze Age and are believed to refer to the Mycenaean civilization or some part of it.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] In the historical period, the term fell into disuse as a general term for Greek people, and was generally reserved for inhabitants of the region of Achaea, a region in the north-central part of the Peloponnese.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] The city-states of this region later formed a confederation known as the Achaean League, which was influential during the 3rd and 2nd centuries BC.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] According to Margalit Finkelberg, the name Ἀχαιοί (earlier Ἀχαιϝοί) is possibly derived, via an intermediate form *Ἀχαϝyοί, from a hypothetical older Greek form reflected in the Hittite form *Aḫḫiyawā*; the latter is attested in the Hittite archives, e.g. in the Tawagalawa letter.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] Beekes doubted its validity and suggested a Pre-Greek **Akaywa-*.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] In Homer, the term Achaeans is one of the primary terms used to refer to the Greeks as a whole.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] It is used 598 times in the *Iliad*, often accompanied by the epithet "long-haired".
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] Other common names used in Homer are **Danaans** (/ˈdæneɪ.ənz/; Δαναοί *Danaoi*; used 138 times in the *Iliad*) and **Argives** (/ˈɑːrɡaɪvz/; Ἀργεῖοι *Argeioi*; used 182 times in the *Iliad*).
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] **Panhellenes** (Πανέλληνες *Panhellenes,* "All of the Greeks") and **Hellenes** (/ˈhɛliːnz/; Ἕλληνες *Hellenes*) both appear only once.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] All of the aforementioned terms were used synonymously to denote a common Greek identity.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] In some English translations of the *Iliad*, the Achaeans are simply called the **Greeks** throughout.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] Later, by the Archaic and Classical periods, the term "Achaeans" referred to inhabitants of the much smaller region of Achaea.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] Herodotus identified the Achaeans of the northern Peloponnese as descendants of the earlier, Homeric Achaeans.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] According to Pausanias, writing in the 2nd century AD, the term "Achaean" was originally given to those Greeks inhabiting the Argolis and Laconia.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] Pausanias and Herodotus both recount the legend that the Achaeans were forced from their homelands by the Dorians, during the legendary Dorian invasion of the Peloponnese.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] They then moved into the region later called Achaea.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] A scholarly consensus has not yet been reached on the origin of the historic Achaeans relative to the Homeric Achaeans and is still hotly debated.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] Former emphasis on presumed race, such as John A.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] Scott's article about the blond locks of the Achaeans as compared to the dark locks of "Mediterranean" Poseidon, on the basis of hints in Homer, has been rejected by some.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] The contrasting belief that "Achaeans", as understood through Homer, is "a name without a country", an *ethnos* created in the Epic tradition, has modern supporters among those who conclude that "Achaeans" were redefined in the 5th century BC, as contemporary speakers of Aeolic Greek.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] Karl Beloch suggested there was no Dorian invasion, but rather that the Peloponnesian Dorians were the Achaeans.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] Eduard Meyer, disagreeing with Beloch, instead put forth the suggestion that the real-life Achaeans were mainland pre-Dorian Greeks.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] His conclusion is based on his research on the similarity between the languages of the Achaeans and pre-historic Arcadians.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] William Prentice disagreed with both, noting archeological evidence suggests the Achaeans instead migrated from "southern Asia Minor to Greece, probably settling first in lower Thessaly" probably prior to 2000 BC.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] Some Hittite texts mention a nation to the west called **Ahhiyawa** (Hittite: 𒄴𒄭𒅀𒉿 *Aḫḫiyawa*).
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] In the earliest reference to this land, a letter outlining the treaty violations of the Hittite vassal Madduwatta, it is called *Ahhiya*.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] Another important example is the *Tawagalawa Letter* written by an unnamed Hittite king, most probably Hattusili III, of the empire period, the 14th–13th century BC, to the king of *Ahhiyawa*, treating him as an equal and implying Miletus (*Millawanda*) was under his control.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] It also refers to an earlier "*Wilusa* episode" involving hostility on the part of *Ahhiyawa*.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] Ahhiya(wa) has been identified with the Achaeans of the Trojan War and the city of Wilusa with the legendary city of Troy.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] Note the similarity with early Greek Ϝιλιον *Wilion*, later Ἴλιον *Ilion*, the name of the acropolis of Troy.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] Emil Forrer, a Swiss Hittitologist who worked on the Boghazköy tablets in Berlin, said the Achaeans of pre-Homeric Greece were directly associated with the term "Land of Ahhiyawa" mentioned in the Hittite texts.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] His conclusions at the time were challenged by other Hittitologists (i.e.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] Johannes Friedrich in 1927 and Albrecht Götze in 1930), as well as by Ferdinand Sommer, who published his *Die Ahhijava-Urkunden* (*The Ahhiyawa Documents*) in 1932.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] The exact relationship of the term *Ahhiyawa* to the Achaeans beyond a similarity in pronunciation was hotly debated by scholars, even following the discovery that Mycenaean Linear B is an early form of Greek; the earlier debate was summed up in 1984 by Hans G.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] More recent research based on new readings and interpretations of the Hittite texts, as well as of the material evidence for Mycenaean contacts with the Anatolian mainland, has led to the widely supported conclusion that Ahhiyawa refers to the Mycenaean world, or at least to a part of it.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] Scholars have proposed several possible locations for the Ahhiyawa capital: Rhodes in the Dodecanese Mycenae in the Argolid and Thebes in Boeotia.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] It is possible that the political center of Ahhiyawa was not fixed in a single location, but may have shifted over time—perhaps initially based in Thebes and later in Mycenae.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] It has been proposed that *Ekwesh* of the Egyptian records may relate to *Achaea* (compared to Hittite *Ahhiyawa*), whereas *Denyen* and *Tanaju* may relate to Classical Greek *Danaoi*.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] The earliest textual reference to the Mycenaean world is in the Annals of Thutmosis III (c.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] 1479–1425 BC), which refers to messengers from the king of the Tanaju, c.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] 1437 BC, offering greeting gifts to the Egyptian king, in order to initiate diplomatic relations, when the latter campaigned in Syria.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] Tanaju is also listed in an inscription at the Mortuary Temple of Amenhotep III.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] A list of the cities and regions of the Tanaju is mentioned in this inscription.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] Among the cities listed are Mycenae, Nauplion, Kythera, Messenia and the Thebaid (region of Thebes).
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] During the 5th year of Pharaoh Merneptah, a confederation of Libyan and northern peoples is supposed to have attacked the western delta.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] Included amongst the ethnic names of the repulsed invaders is the Ekwesh or Eqwesh, whom some have seen as Achaeans, although Egyptian texts specifically mention these Ekwesh to be circumcised.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] Homer mentions an Achaean attack upon the delta.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] Menelaus speaks of the same in Book IV of the *Odyssey* to Telemachus when he recounts his own return home from the Trojan War.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] Some ancient Greek authors say that Helen had spent the time of the Trojan War in Egypt, and not at Troy, and that after Troy the Greeks went there to recover her.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] In Greek mythology, the perceived cultural divisions among the Hellenes were represented as legendary lines of descent that identified kinship groups, with each line being derived from an eponymous ancestor.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] Hellen, Graikos, Magnes, and Macedon were sons of Deucalion and Pyrrha, the only people who survived the Great Flood.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] The *ethne* were said to have originally been named *Graikoi* after the elder son but later renamed *Hellenes* after Hellen who was proved to be the strongest.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] The sons of Hellen and the nymph Orseis were Dorus, Xuthos, and Aeolus.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] The sons of Xuthos and Kreousa, daughter of Erechthea, were Ion and Achaeus.
[src:aeneid/achaeans-homer] According to Hyginus, 22 Achaeans killed 362 Trojans during their ten years at Troy.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The ***Aeneid*** (/ɪˈniːɪd/ *ih-NEE-id*; Latin: *Aeneis* [ae̯ˈneːɪs]) is a Latin epic poem that tells the legendary story of Aeneas, a Trojan who fled the fall of Troy and travelled to Italy, where he became the ancestor of the Romans.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Written by the Roman poet Virgil between 29 and 19 BC, the *Aeneid* comprises 9,896 lines in dactylic hexameter.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The first six of its twelve books tell the story of Aeneas' wanderings from Troy to Italy, and the latter six tell of the Trojans' ultimately victorious war upon the Latins, under whose name Aeneas and his Trojan followers are destined to be subsumed.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The hero Aeneas was already known to Graeco-Roman legend and myth, having been a character in the *Iliad*.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The *Aeneid* is widely regarded as Virgil's masterpiece and one of the greatest works of Latin literature.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Although the definitive story of Aeneas escaping the fallen Troy and finding a new home in Italy, thus eventually becoming the ancestor of the Romans, was codified by Virgil, the myth of Aeneas' post-Troy adventures predates him by centuries.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] As Greek settlements began to expand starting in the sixth century BC, Greek colonists would often try to connect their new homes, and the native people they found there, to their pre-existing mythology; the *Odyssey* containing Odysseus's travels in many far away lands already provided such a link.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Aeneas's story reflects not just Roman, but rather a combination of various Greek, Etruscan, Latin and Roman elements.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Troy provided for a very suitable narrative for the Greek colonists in Magna Graecia and Sicily who wished to link their new homelands with themselves, and the Etruscans, who would have adopted the story of Aeneas in Italy first, and quickly became associated with him.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Greek vases as early as the sixth century BC provide evidence for these early Greek mythological accounts of Aeneas founding a new home in Etruria predating Virgil by a wide margin, and he was known to have been worshipped in Lavinium, the city he founded.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The discovery of thirteen large altars in Lavinium indicates early Greek influence, dating to the sixth through fourth century BC.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] In the following centuries, the Romans would come in contact with Greek colonies, conquer them and subsume the legend of Aeneas into their own mythological narratives.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Literary evidence of a pre-Virgil attestation of Aeneas' journey can also be found.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] A fragment usually attributed to the fifth-century BC logographer Hellanicus of Lesbos' lost *History of the Priestesses of Argos* states that Rome was founded by Aeneas with the help of Odysseus and named after Rhome, a Trojan woman Aeneas was acquainted with.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The attribution of this passage to Hellanicus has been met with some doubt and rejection, but other scholars are less dismissive.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Around the fourth century BC, an otherwise unknown Alcimus apparently made Aeneas the father of Romulus by Thyrrenia.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Romulus' then grandson Rhomus (Remus) went on to found Rome.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The *Aeneid* can be divided into halves based on the disparate subject matter of Books 1–6 (Aeneas' journey to Latium in Italy), commonly associated with Homer's *Odyssey*, and Books 7–12 (the war in Latium), mirroring the *Iliad*.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] These two halves are commonly regarded as reflecting Virgil's ambition to rival Homer by treating both the *Odyssey*'s wandering theme and the *Iliad*'s warfare themes.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] This is, however, a rough correspondence.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Virgil begins his poem with a statement of his theme (*Arma virumque cano**...*, "Of arms and the man I sing ...") and an invocation to the Muse, falling some seven lines after the poem's inception (**Musa, mihi causas memora* ...*, "O Muse, recount to me the causes ...").
[src:aeneid/aeneid] He then explains the reason for the principal conflict in the story: the resentment held by the goddess Juno against the Trojan people.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] This is consistent with her role throughout the Homeric epics.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] In the manner of Homeric epic, the story begins *in medias res* (into the middle of things), with the Trojan fleet in the eastern Mediterranean, heading in the direction of Italy.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The fleet, led by Aeneas, is on a voyage to find a second home.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] It has been foretold that in Italy he will give rise to a race both noble and courageous, a race which will become known to all nations.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Juno is wrathful, because she had not been chosen in the judgement of Paris, and because her favourite city, Carthage, will be destroyed by Aeneas' descendants.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Also, Ganymede, a Trojan prince, was chosen to be the cupbearer to her husband, Jupiter—replacing Juno's daughter, Hebe.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Juno proceeds to Aeolus, King of the Winds, and asks that he release the winds to stir up a storm in exchange for a bribe (Deiopea, the loveliest of all her sea nymphs, as a wife).
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Aeolus agrees to carry out Juno's orders (line 77, "My task is / To fulfill your commands"); the storm then devastates the fleet.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Neptune takes notice: although he himself is no friend of the Trojans, he is infuriated by Juno's intrusion into his domain, and stills the winds and calms the waters, after making sure that the winds would not bother the Trojans again, lest they be punished more harshly than they were this time.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The fleet takes shelter on the coast of Africa, where Aeneas rouses the spirits of his men, reassuring them that they have been through worse situations before.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] There, Aeneas' mother, Venus, in the form of a huntress very similar to the goddess Diana, encourages him and recounts to him the history of Carthage.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Eventually, Aeneas ventures into the city, and in the temple of Juno he seeks and gains the favour of Dido, queen of the city.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The city has only recently been founded by refugees from Tyre and will later become a great imperial rival and enemy to Rome.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] She goes to her son, Aeneas' half-brother Cupid, and tells him to imitate Ascanius (the son of Aeneas and his first wife Creusa).
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Thus disguised, Cupid goes to Dido and offers the gifts expected from a guest.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] As Dido cradles the boy during a banquet given in honour of the Trojans, Cupid secretly weakens her sworn fidelity to the soul of her late husband Sychaeus, who was murdered by her brother Pygmalion back in Tyre, by inciting fresh love for Aeneas.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] In books 2 and 3, Aeneas recounts to Dido the events that occasioned the Trojans' arrival.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Cunning Ulysses devised a way for Greek warriors to gain entry into the walled city of Troy by hiding in a large wooden horse.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The Greeks pretended to sail away, leaving a warrior, Sinon, to mislead the Trojans into believing that the horse was an offering and that if it were taken into the city, the Trojans would be able to conquer Greece.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The Trojan priest Laocoön saw through the Greek plot and urged the horse's destruction, but his protests fell on deaf ears, so he hurled his spear at the horse.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Then, in what would be seen by the Trojans as punishment from the gods, two serpents emerged from the sea and devoured Laocoön, along with his two sons.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The Trojans then took the horse inside the fortified walls, and after nightfall the armed Greeks emerged from it, opening the city's gates to allow the returned Greek army to slaughter the Trojans.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] In a dream, Hector, the fallen Trojan prince, advised Aeneas to flee with his family.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Aeneas awoke and saw with horror what was happening to his beloved city.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] At first he tried to fight the enemy, but soon he lost his comrades and was left alone to fend off the Greeks.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] He witnessed the murder of Priam by Achilles' son Pyrrhus.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] His mother, Venus, interrupted him when he was about to murder Helen, and led him back to his house.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Aeneas tells of his escape with his son, Ascanius, his wife Creusa, and his father, Anchises, after the occurrence of various omens (Ascanius' head catching fire without his being harmed, a clap of thunder and a shooting star).
[src:aeneid/aeneid] At the city gates, they notice that they have lost Creusa, and Aeneas has to re-enter the city in order to look for her.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] To his sorrow, he encounters only her ghost, who tells him that his destiny is to reach Hesperia, where kingship and a royal spouse await him.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] This last city had been built in an attempt to replicate Troy.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] In Buthrotum, Aeneas meets Andromache, the widow of Hector.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] She is still lamenting the loss of her valiant husband and beloved child.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] There, too, Aeneas sees and meets Helenus, one of Priam's sons, who has the gift of prophecy.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Through him, Aeneas learns the destiny laid out for him: he is divinely advised to seek out the land of Italy (also known as *Ausonia* or *Hesperia*), where his descendants will not only prosper, but in time rule the entire known world.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] In addition, Helenus also bids him to go to the Sibyl in Cumae.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Heading into the open sea, Aeneas leaves Buthrotum, rounds the south eastern tip of Italy and makes his way towards Sicily (Trinacria).
[src:aeneid/aeneid] There, they are caught in the whirlpool of Charybdis and driven out to sea.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Soon they come ashore at the land of the Cyclopes.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] There they meet a Greek, Achaemenides, one of Ulysses' men, who has been left behind when his comrades escaped the cave of Polyphemus.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] They take Achaemenides on board and narrowly escape Polyphemus.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Shortly after, at Drepanum, Aeneas' father Anchises dies of old age.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Aeneas heads on (towards Italy) and gets deflected to Carthage (by the storm described in book 1).
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Here, Aeneas ends his account of his wanderings to Dido.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Dido realises that she has fallen in love with Aeneas.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Juno seizes upon this opportunity to make a deal with Venus, Aeneas' mother, with the intention of distracting Aeneas from his destiny of founding a city in Italy.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Aeneas is inclined to return Dido's love, and during a hunting expedition, a storm created by Juno drives them into a cave, where Juno presides over a ceremony in which natural phenomena imitate the symbols of a marriage ceremony.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Fama (the personification of rumour) spreads the news of Aeneas and Dido's marriage, which eventually reaches King Iarbas.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Iarbas, who also sought relations with Dido but was rejected, angrily prays to his father Jupiter to express his feeling that his worship of Jupiter has not earned him the rewards he deserves.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] As a result, Jupiter sends Mercury to remind Aeneas of his duty, leaving him no choice but to depart.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] When Aeneas clandestinely begins making preparations to leave at the behest of Mercury, Dido discovers Aeneas' intentions.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Enraged and heartbroken, she accuses Aeneas of infidelity while also imploring him to stay.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Aeneas responds by attempting to explain that his duty is important and that he does not leave of his own volition, but Dido is not satisfied.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Ultimately, her heart broken, Dido commits suicide by stabbing herself upon a pyre with Aeneas' sword.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Before dying, she predicts eternal strife between Aeneas' people and hers; "rise up from my bones, avenging spirit" (4.625, trans.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Fitzgerald) is a possible invocation to Hannibal.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Looking back from the deck of his ship, Aeneas sees the smoke of Dido's funeral pyre, and although he does not understand the exact reason behind it, he understands it as a bad omen, considering the angry madness of her love.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Hindered by bad weather from reaching Italy, the Trojans return to where they started at the beginning of book 1.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Book 5 then takes place on Sicily and centres on the funeral games that Aeneas organises for the anniversary of his father's death.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Aeneas organises celebratory games for the men—a boat race, a foot race, a boxing match, and an archery contest.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] In all those contests, Aeneas is careful to reward winners and losers, showing his leadership qualities by not allowing antagonism even after foul play.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Afterwards, Ascanius leads the boys in a military parade and mock battle, the Lusus Troiae—a tradition he will teach the Latins while building the walls of Alba Longa.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] During these events, Juno, via her messenger Iris, who disguises herself as an old woman, incites the Trojan women to burn the fleet and prevent the Trojans from ever reaching Italy, but her plan is thwarted when Ascanius and Aeneas intervene.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Aeneas prays to Jupiter to quench the fires, which the god does with a torrential rainstorm.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] An anxious Aeneas is comforted by a vision of his father, who tells him to go to the underworld to receive a vision of his and Rome's future.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] In return for safe passage to Italy, the gods, by order of Jupiter, will receive one of Aeneas' men as a sacrifice: Palinurus, who steers Aeneas' ship by night, is put to sleep by Somnus and falls overboard.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Aeneas, with the guidance of the Cumaean Sibyl, descends into the underworld.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] They pass by crowds of the dead by the banks of the river Acheron and are ferried across by Charon before passing by Cerberus, the three-headed guardian of the underworld.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Then Aeneas is shown the fates of the wicked in Tartarus and is warned by the Sibyl to bow to the justice of the gods.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] He also meets the shade of Dido, who remains irreconcilable.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] He is then brought to green fields of Elysium.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] There he speaks with the spirit of his father and is offered a prophetic vision of the destiny of Rome.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Upon returning to the land of the living, Aeneas leads the Trojans to settle in Latium, where King Latinus received oracles pointing towards the arrival of strangers and bidding him to marry his daughter Lavinia to the foreigners, and not to Turnus, the ruler of another native people, the Rutuli.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Juno, unhappy with the Trojans' favourable situation, summons the fury Alecto from the underworld to stir up a war between the Trojans and the locals.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Alecto incites Amata, the Queen of Latium and the wife of Latinus, to demand that Lavinia be married to noble Turnus, brings forth anger in Turnus which spurs him to war with the Trojans, and causes Ascanius to wound a revered deer during a hunt.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Hence, although Aeneas wishes to avoid a war, hostilities break out.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The book closes with a catalogue of Italic warriors.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Given the impending war, Aeneas seeks help from the Tuscans, enemies of the Rutuli, after having been encouraged to do so in a dream by Tiberinus.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] At the place where Rome will be, he meets a friendly Greek, King Evander of Arcadia.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Evander sends his son Pallas to join Aeneas and lead troops against the Rutuli.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Venus urges her spouse Vulcan to create weapons for Aeneas, which she then presents to Aeneas as a gift.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] On the shield, the future history of Rome is depicted.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Meanwhile, the Trojan camp is attacked by Turnus—spurred on by Juno, who informs him that Aeneas is away from his camp—and a midnight raid by the Trojans Nisus and Euryalus on Turnus' camp leads to their death.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The next day, Turnus manages to breach the gates but is forced to retreat by jumping into the Tiber.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] A council of the gods is held, in which Venus and Juno speak before Jupiter, and Aeneas returns to the besieged Trojan camp accompanied by his new Arcadian and Tuscan allies.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] In the ensuing battle many are slain—notably Pallas, whom Evander has entrusted to Aeneas but who is killed by Turnus.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Mezentius, Turnus' close associate, allows his son Lausus to be killed by Aeneas while he himself flees.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] He reproaches himself and faces Aeneas in single combat—an honourable but essentially futile endeavour leading to his death.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] After a short break in which the funeral ceremony for Pallas takes place, the war continues.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Another notable native, Camilla, an Amazon character and virgin devoted to Diana, fights bravely but is killed by Aruns, who in turn is struck dead by Diana's sentinel Opis.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Single combat is proposed between Aeneas and Turnus, but Aeneas is so obviously superior to Turnus that the Rutuli, urged on by Turnus' divine sister, Juturna—who in turn is instigated by Juno—break the truce.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Aeneas is injured by an arrow but is soon healed with the help of his mother Venus and returns to the battle.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Turnus and Aeneas dominate the battle on opposite wings, but when Aeneas makes a daring attack at the city of Latium (causing the queen of Latium to hang herself in despair), he forces Turnus into single combat once more.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] In the duel, Turnus' strength deserts him as he tries to hurl a rock, and Aeneas' spear goes through his thigh.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] As Turnus is on his knees, begging for his life, the epic ends with Aeneas initially tempted to obey Turnus' pleas to spare his life, but then killing him in rage when he sees that Turnus is wearing Aeneas' friend Pallas' belt over his shoulder as a trophy.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Critics of the *Aeneid* focus on a variety of issues.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The tone of the poem as a whole is a particular matter of debate; some see the poem as ultimately pessimistic and politically subversive to the Augustan regime, while others view it as a celebration of the new imperial dynasty.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Virgil makes use of the symbolism of the Augustan regime, and some scholars see strong associations between Augustus and Aeneas, the one as founder and the other as re-founder of Rome.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] A strong teleology, or drive towards a climax, has been detected in the poem.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The *Aeneid* is full of prophecies about the future of Rome, the deeds of Augustus, his ancestors, and famous Romans, and the Carthaginian Wars; the shield of Aeneas even depicts Augustus' victory at Actium in 31 BC.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] A further focus of study is the character of Aeneas.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The *Aeneid* appears to have been a great success.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Virgil is said to have recited Books 2, 4 and 6 to Augustus; the mention of her son, Marcellus, in book 6 apparently caused Augustus' sister Octavia to faint.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The poem was unfinished when Virgil died in 19 BC.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] According to tradition, Virgil travelled to Greece around 19 BC to revise the *Aeneid*.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] After meeting Augustus in Athens and deciding to return home, Virgil caught a fever while visiting a town near Megara.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Virgil crossed to Italy by ship, weakened with disease, and died in Brundisium harbour on 21 September 19 BC, leaving a wish that the manuscript of the *Aeneid* was to be burned.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Augustus ordered Virgil's literary executors, Lucius Varius Rufus and Plotius Tucca, to disregard that wish, instead ordering the *Aeneid* to be published with as few editorial changes as possible.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The *Aeneid* was written in a time of major political and social change in Rome, with the fall of the Roman Republic and the War of Actium having torn through society and many Romans' faith in the "Greatness of Rome" severely faltering.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] However, the new emperor, Augustus Caesar, began to institute a new era of prosperity and peace, specifically through the re-introduction of traditional Roman moral values.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The *Aeneid* was seen as reflecting this aim, by depicting the heroic Aeneas as a man devoted and loyal to his country and its prominence, rather than his own personal gains.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Le Guin (in her 2008 novel *Lavinia*) to compose their own supplements.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Despite the polished and complex nature of the *Aeneid* (legend stating that Virgil wrote only three lines of the poem each day), the number of half-complete lines and the abrupt ending are generally seen as evidence that Virgil died before he could finish the work.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The friends did not comply with Virgil's wishes and Augustus himself ordered that they be disregarded.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] After minor modifications, the *Aeneid* was published.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Because it was composed and preserved in writing rather than orally, the text exhibits less variation than other classical epics.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] As with other classical Latin poetry, the meter is based on the length of syllables rather than the stress, though the interplay of meter and stress is also important.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Virgil also incorporated such poetic devices as alliteration, onomatopoeia, synecdoche, assonance, and hyperbole.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Furthermore, he uses personification, metaphor, and simile in his work, usually to add drama and tension to the scene.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] An example of a simile can be found in book II when Aeneas is compared to a shepherd who stood on the high top of a rock unaware of what is going on around him.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] It can be seen that just as the shepherd is a protector of his sheep, so too is Aeneas to his people.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] As was the rule in classical antiquity, an author's style was seen as an expression of his personality and character.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Virgil's Latin has been praised for its evenness, subtlety and dignity.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The *Aeneid*, like other classical epics, is written in dactylic hexameters: each line consists of six metrical feet made up of dactyls (one long syllable followed by two short syllables) and spondees (two long syllables).
[src:aeneid/aeneid] This epic consists of twelve books, and the narrative is broken up into three sections of four books each, respectively addressing Dido; the Trojans' arrival in Italy; and the war with the Latins.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The *Aeneid* comes to an abrupt ending, and scholars have speculated that Virgil died before he could finish the poem.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The Roman ideal of *pietas* ("piety, dutiful respect"), which can be loosely translated from the Latin as a selfless sense of duty toward one's filial, religious, and societal obligations, was a crux of ancient Roman morality.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Throughout the *Aeneid*, Aeneas serves as the embodiment of *pietas*, with the phrase "pious Aeneas" occurring 20 times throughout the poem, thereby fulfilling his capacity as the father of the Roman people.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] However, Aeneas' *pietas* extends beyond his devotion to his father: we also see several examples of his religious fervour.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] In addition to his religious and familial *pietas*, Aeneas also displays fervent patriotism and devotion to his people, particularly in a military capacity.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] For instance, as he and his followers leave Troy, Aeneas swears that he will "take up / The combat once again.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Aeneas is a symbol of *pietas* in all of its forms, serving as a moral paragon to whom a Roman should aspire.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] One of the most recurring themes in the *Aeneid* is that of divine intervention.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Throughout the poem, the gods are constantly influencing the main characters and trying to change and impact the outcome, regardless of the fate that they all know will occur.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] For example, Juno comes down and acts as a phantom Aeneas to drive Turnus away from the real Aeneas and all of his rage from the death of Pallas.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Even though Juno knows in the end that Aeneas will triumph over Turnus, she does all she can to delay and avoid this outcome.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Divine intervention occurs multiple times, in Book 4 especially.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Aeneas falls in love with Dido, delaying his ultimate fate of travelling to Italy.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Juno is speaking to Venus, making an agreement and influencing the lives and emotions of both Dido and Aeneas.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Later in the same book, Jupiter steps in and restores what is the true fate and path for Aeneas, sending Mercury down to Aeneas' dreams, telling him that he must travel to Italy and leave his new-found lover.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Several of the gods try to intervene against the powers of fate, even though they know what the eventual outcome will be.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The interventions are really just distractions to continue the conflict and postpone the inevitable.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] If the gods represent humans, just as the human characters engage in conflicts and power struggles, so too do the gods.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Fate, described as a preordained destiny that men and gods have to follow, is a major theme in the *Aeneid*.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] One example is when Aeneas is reminded of his fate through Jupiter and Mercury while he is falling in love with Dido.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] There is a marked difference between fate and divine intervention, as even though the gods might remind mortals of their eventual fate, the gods themselves are not in control of it.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] For example, the opening lines of the poem specify that Aeneas "came to Italy by destiny", but is also harassed by the separate force of "baleful Juno in her sleepless rage".
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Even though Juno might intervene, Aeneas' fate is set in stone and cannot be changed.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] From the very beginning of the *Aeneid*, violence and conflict are used as a means of survival and conquest.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Aeneas' voyage is caused by the Trojan War and the destruction of Troy.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Aeneas describes to Dido in Book 2 the massive amount of destruction that occurs after the Greeks sneak into Troy.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] He recalls that he asks his men to "defend / A city lost in flames.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Come, let us die, / We'll make a rush into the thick of it." This is one of the first demonstrations of the way in which violence begets violence: even though the Trojans know they have lost the battle, they continue to fight for their country.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] This violence continues as Aeneas makes his journey.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Dido kills herself in order to end and escape her worldly problem: being heartbroken over the departure of Aeneas and now left alone, surrounded by violent rulers who desire her and her throne.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Queen Dido's suicide is a double edged sword.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Furthermore, her people, hearing of their queen's death, have only one avenue on which to direct the blame: the already-departed Trojans.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Thus, Dido's request of her people and her people's only recourse for closure align in their mutual hate for Aeneas and his Trojans.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] In effect, Dido's violent suicide leads to the violent nature of the later relationship between Carthage and Rome.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Finally, when Aeneas arrives in Latium, conflict inevitably arises.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Juno sends Alecto, one of the Furies, to cause Turnus to go against Aeneas.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] In the ensuing battles, Turnus kills Pallas, who is supposed to be under Aeneas' protection.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] This act of violence causes Aeneas to be consumed with fury.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] This final act of violence shows how Turnus' violence—the act of killing Pallas—inevitably leads to more violence and his own death.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] It is possible that the recurring theme of violence in the *Aeneid* is a subtle commentary on the bloody violence contemporary readers would have just experienced during the Late Republican civil wars.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The *Aeneid* potentially explores whether the violence of the civil wars was necessary to establish a lasting peace under Augustus, or whether it would just lead to more violence in the future.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Written during the reign of Augustus, the *Aeneid* presents the hero Aeneas as a strong and powerful leader.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The favourable representation of Aeneas parallels Augustus in that it portrays his reign in a progressive and admirable light, and allows Augustus to be positively associated with the portrayal of Aeneas.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Although Virgil's patron Maecenas was obviously not Augustus himself, he was still a high figure within Augustus' administration and could have personally benefitted from representing Aeneas in a positive light.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] In the *Aeneid*, Aeneas is portrayed as the singular hope for the rebirth of the Trojan people.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Charged with the preservation of his people by divine authority, Aeneas is symbolic of Augustus' own accomplishments in establishing order after the prolonged chaos of the Roman civil wars towards the end of the Roman Republic.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Augustus as the light of saviour and the last hope of the Roman people is a parallel to Aeneas as the saviour of the Trojans.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Later in Book 6, Aeneas travels to the underworld where he sees his father Anchises, who tells him of his own destiny as well as that of the Roman people.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Virgil writes about the fated future of Lavinium, the city that Aeneas will found, which will in turn lead directly to the golden reign of Augustus.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Virgil is using a form of literary propaganda to demonstrate the Augustan regime's destiny to bring glory and peace to Rome.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Rather than use Aeneas indirectly as a positive parallel to Augustus as in other parts of the poem, Virgil outright praises the emperor in Book 6, referring to Augustus as a harbinger for the glory of Rome and new levels of prosperity.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The poem abounds with smaller and greater allegories.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Two of the debated allegorical sections pertain to the exit from the underworld and to Pallas' belt.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] In an extension of the latter interpretation, it has been suggested that Virgil is conveying that the history of the world since the foundation of Rome is but a lie.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Other scholars claim that Virgil is establishing that the theological implications of the preceding scene (an apparent system of reincarnation) are not to be taken as literal.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] This section has been interpreted to mean that for the entire passage of the poem, Aeneas, who symbolises *pietas* (piety or morality), in a moment becomes *furor* (fury), thus destroying what is essentially the primary theme of the poem itself.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Many have argued over these two sections.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The *Aeneid* is a cornerstone of the Western canon, and early (at least by the 2nd century AD) became one of the essential elements of a Latin education, usually required to be memorised.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Even after the decline of the Roman Empire, it "remained central to a Latin education".
[src:aeneid/aeneid] In Latin-Christian culture, the *Aeneid* was one of the canonical texts, subjected to commentary as a philological and educational study, with the most complete commentary having been written by the 4th-century grammarian Maurus Servius Honoratus.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] It was widely held to be the pinnacle of Latin literature, much in the same way that the *Iliad* was seen to be supreme in Greek literature.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The strong influence of the *Aeneid* has been identified in the development of European vernacular literatures—some English works that show its influence being *Beowulf*, Layamon's *Brut* (through the source text *Historia Regum Britanniae*), *The Faerie Queene*, and John Milton's *Paradise Lost*.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Another continental work displaying the influence of the *Aeneid* is the 16th-century Portuguese epic *Os Lusíadas*, written by Luís de Camões and dealing with Vasco da Gama's voyage to India.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Many phrases from this poem entered the Latin language, much as passages from William Shakespeare and Alexander Pope have entered the English language.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] One example is from Aeneas' reaction to a painting of the sack of Troy: *Sunt lacrimae rerum et mentem mortalia tangunt*—"These are the tears of things, and our mortality cuts to the heart" (*Aeneid* I, 462).
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The first full and faithful rendering of the poem in an Anglic language is the Scots translation by Gavin Douglas—his *Eneados*, completed in 1513, which also included Maffeo Vegio's supplement.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Even in the 20th century, Ezra Pound considered this still to be the best *Aeneid* translation, praising the "richness and fervour" of its language and its hallmark fidelity to the original.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The English translation by the 17th-century poet John Dryden is another important version.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Most classic translations, including both Douglas and Dryden, employ a rhyme scheme; most more modern attempts do not.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Powell (2015); David Ferry (2017); Len Krisak (2020); Shadi Bartsch (2021); as well as Scott McGill and Susannah Wright (2025).
[src:aeneid/aeneid] There have also been partial translations, such as those by Henry Howard, Earl of Surrey (Book 2 and Book 4), and Seamus Heaney (Book 6).
[src:aeneid/aeneid] One of the first operas based on the story of the *Aeneid* was the English composer Henry Purcell's *Dido and Aeneas* (1688).
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The opera is famous for its aria "Dido's Lament" ('When I am laid in earth'), of which the first line of the melody is inscribed on the wall by the door of the Purcell Room, a concert hall in London.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The story of the *Aeneid* was made into the grand opera *Les Troyens* (1856–1858) by the French composer Hector Berlioz.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The *Aeneid* was the basis for the 1962 Italian film *The Avenger* and the 1971–1972 television serial *Eneide*.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] In the musical *Spring Awakening*, based on the play of the same title by Frank Wedekind, schoolboys study the Latin text, and the first verse of Book 1 is incorporated into the number "All That's Known".
[src:aeneid/aeneid] Ursula Le Guin's 2008 novel *Lavinia* is a free prose retelling of the last six books of the *Aeneid* narrated by and centred on Aeneas' Latin wife Lavinia, a minor character in the epic poem.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] It carries the action forward to the crowning of Aeneas' younger son Silvius as king of Latium.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] A 17th-century popular broadside ballad also appears to recount events from books 1–4 of the *Aeneid,* focusing mostly on the relationship between Aeneas and Dido.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] The ballad, "The Wandering Prince of Troy", presents many similar elements as Virgil's epic, but alters Dido's final sentiments toward Aeneas, as well as presenting an interesting end for Aeneas himself.
[src:aeneid/aeneid] A number of parodies and travesties of the *Aeneid* have been made.
